<speak version="1.0" xml:lang="en-US">
  <voice name="en-US-Ava:DragonHDLatestNeural">
    Every cross-boundary trust architecture eventually asks the same question: <emphasis level="moderate">who is in charge</emphasis>?
    <break time="550ms"/>
    Two financial institutions may need to cooperate, but neither wants the other identity provider in its trust chain. A shared broker looks simple, until both organizations accept someone else key management, uptime, and revocation rules.
    <break time="550ms"/>
    <emphasis level="moderate">Sovereign systems</emphasis> reject that tradeoff. Each operator keeps its own keys, its own recognition policy, and its own revocation decisions.
    <break time="550ms"/>
    Genesis Mesh lets sovereigns cooperate through signed recognition, not centralized control. They can recognize one another, exchange attestations, and revoke trust without surrendering local authority.
    <break time="550ms"/>
    The value is not isolation. The value is joining a recognition network <emphasis level="moderate">without giving up sovereignty</emphasis>.
  </voice>
</speak>
